Formulation of the “opine” concept (

) made the fundamental connection between a particular agrobacterial Ti plasmid and the genes encoded on the T-DNA portion that is inserted into the plant genome. Most of the known opines such as octopine, nopaline, leucinopine, mannopine etc. are secondary amines, formed by the reductive conjugation of either the carbonyl of an α- keto acid (or a reducing sugar aldehyde) condensation product with the α- amino group of an L-amino acid. They were isolated individually from tumours incited by various pathogenic strains of 

Agrobacterium radiobacter
(Beijerinck and van Delden) Conn

            Rhizobiaceae
(formerly 

A. tumefaciens
(Smith and Townsend) Conn

). Thus the “opine” concept led to the realisation that by “engineering” the plant’ s metabolic activities, the bacterium forces the plant to provide nitrogen in a 
form that
only the bacterium can catabolise. Considerations by 

predicted and confirmed that other opines must exist in plant tumours and two different carbohydrate phospho-diesters, agrocinopine A and agrocinopine C, were discovered, each one providing both a phosphorus source and an energy source (carbohydrate) for the tumour-inciting bacteria. The complete structure of agrocinopine A was published by 

and an Honours degree project on agrocinopine C was submitted by the late Anna E. Savage (A.E.S.; 

). The discovery of 

Agrobacterium

-derived T-DNA genes in the genomes of all 291 cultivated sweet potato accessions tested, including a gene showing significant similarity to a Ti-plasmid encoded agrocinopine synthase gene (
acs
; 

) prompted us to re-examine A.E.S’ s original 1983 agrocinopine C sample using current mass spectrometry and NMR techniques and facilities.

Recent work has provided insight into the close link between the active uptake of agrocinopines into tumour inducing strains of 

Agrobacterium

, via specific transporters, and the “Trojan horse” uptake of the structurally-related, naturally occurring fraudulent adenine-dinucleotide bacteriocin, agrocin 84 (

