R. rhizogenes

strain K1026 also plays a vital role in the commercial biological control of the economically important crown gall disease of plants including stone fruits and roses (

).

We now report the structure of agrocinopine C which is related to, but nevertheless somewhat different from the sucrose phosphodiester structure of agrocinopine A (

). Agrocinopine A is a phospho-diester of sucrose linked from the C4-hydroxyl of the fructo-furanosyl moiety to the C2-hydroxyl of L-arabinose. Agrocinopine B is also a phosphodiester and was obtained from agrocinopine A by acid cleavage of the glucose moiety from the sucrose moiety. The original agrocinopine A structure (

) was initially disputed by 

but later confirmed by Messens et al. (1986), albeit with two mis-attribution errors in key references. In the same context, it should be noted that although agrocinopines each contain three sugar moieties, only the two in sucrose are linked by a glycosidic bond and consequently the agrocinopines A and C should not be referred to as tri-saccharides. Ultimately, the original structure (

) for the L-arabinosyl-phosphodiester of sucrose was unequivocally confirmed by synthesis and shown to be identical in all respects with the natural product agrocinopine A by 

and 

, including its biological activity.

The critical molecular feature determining the specific, active uptake of agrocin 84 and agrocinopines via agrocinopine transporters appears to be a sugar 2-phosphate (

; 

; 

). An additional reason for publishing the structure of agrocinopine C at this time is that recent papers (

; 

; 

) have cited and presented incorrect structures for this molecule based on the previous synthesis of an incorrect version (

). It was apparent that Tate for some time considered that the compound D-glucos-2-yl sucros-2-yl phosphate, synthesised by 

, was the correct structure for agrocinopine C as per Tate’ s correspondence with Lindberg and Norberg in 1990 and later with 

. However, it is now clear that the original structure determined by Savage and Tate (

) was correct and modern NMR spectroscopic methods have confirmed this.

