provided clear 32 P evidence for enhanced uptake of agrocin 84 by the nopaline strain
R. rhizogenes
K57A, after pre-incubation for 4 h with agrocinopine A. In the absence of pre-incubation, agrocinopine A also completely blocked the normal uptake of agrocin 84 by the pathogen K57A, thereby demonstrating that they both entered the cell by the same uptake mechanism. By contrast with the nopaline strain K57A, there was no uptake of agrocin 84 whatsoever in the absence of agrocinopine C by the agropine strain A281. However, pre-incubation of strain A281 for 6 h with a similar concentration of agrocinopine C allowed subsequent uptake of agrocin 84, leading to the toxic effect seen in Fig. 4 . It is apparent that the transport system for uptake of agrocinopine C is normally repressed but is induced when this opine is present. The tumour-inducing plasmid pTiBo542 contains an operon which is homologous to the acc operon of the agrocinopine A-encoding plasmid pTiC58 (
;
). The acc operon of pTiC58 codes for an ABC-type uptake system (genes accA to accE ) and for catabolism of agrocinopine A via genes accF and accG (
). It is evident that the acc operon of pTiBo542 encodes similar functions that enable the uptake and catabolism of agrocinopine C as well as the uptake of agrocin 84. The repressors coded for by the accR genes on pTiC58 and pTiBo542 function differently in that the acc operon on pTi58 (agrocinopine A) is normally partially expressed, whereas it is not expressed on pTiBo542 until agrocinopine C is present. This accounts for the difference between Fig. 4 and
