Electrophoretically homogeneous agrocinopine C was isolated from tumours induced by the pathogenic
Agrobacterium radiobacter
strain K478 as follows. Crude agrocinopine C was obtained from crown gall tissue ( 312 g ), harvested from wounded sunflower-stems that had been previously inoculated with
A. radiobacter
strain K478. The macerated gall tissue was homogenised in 70% v/v ethanol and centrifuged (Sorvall RC-5B at 2310× g for 15 min). The supernatant was collected and combined with three 70% ethanol washes of the pellet. The ethanol was removed by rotary evaporation in vacuo , and residual water insoluble material was removed by filtration through Whatman 541 filter paper. The crude aqueous extract was loaded onto a 500 mL bed of Dowex 1X-2 Anion exchange resin ( 100 g , 25 mm × 300 mm ) in the acetate form, washed with water 2.5 L, and eluted with a volatile acetate buffer (pyridine 0.2 M/acetic acid 0.1 M), ~pH 5, and 10 mL fractions were collected. Biologically active fractions (10 μL subsamples) were detected using Whatman No 1 filter paper squares placed around a centrally located 36 h-old patch culture of
R. rhizogenes
strain K84 on Petri plates of Stonier’ s medium (
) as producer of agrocin 84 to provide a source of this adenine nucleotide antibiotic ( Fig. 4 ). The squares with aliquots of the agrocinopine C ion-exchange eluate fractions were placed on the agar which was then overlaid with the normally insensitive strain K478 and plates were incubated at 27 ◦ C for 2–3 d. Active eluate fractions (100–240) induced agrocin 84 inhibition zones as shown ( Fig. 4 ). Buffer was removed from the bulk sample by evaporation in vacuo at 30 ◦ C to yield a semisolid residue ( 590 mg ), yield 0.19% of the fresh tumour weight. This active residue was dissolved in distilled water (300 mL), loaded onto a 500 mL bed of Dowex 1X- 2 in the bicarbonate form, washed with water (2 L) and eluted into fractions (10 mL) with a linear gradient (0–0.2 M) of NH 4 HCO 3 at pH 9.2. Biologically active material eluted in fractions 130–180 (0.05–0.1 M NH 4 HCO 3 ), in vacuo concentration at 30 ◦ C yielded a dry residue ( 340 mg , 0.11%) of the ammonium salt. This crude agrocinopine C was then eluted with water through a 50 mL Dowex 50 column in the lanthanum form. The un-retained, biologically active, agrocinopine C component eluted in fractions 2, 3 and 4 and was found to be AgNO 3 /NaOEt reagent (
) glycol-positive, molybdate reagent phosphate-positive (
), urea/phosphoric acid reagent (
) ketose-positive, p -anisidine reagent (
) hexose-positive. Its electrophoretic mobility ( RmOG ) at pH 1.7 was 0.43, and yield was 158 mg (0.05%). Repetitive preparative electrophoresis in the volatile formic acetic buffer (pH 1.7) with subsequent elution, neutralisation with ammonia and drying, yielded 57.3 mg (0.02%) of electrophoretically homogeneous agrocinopine C.

